<p><strong>Notes to editors</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The road and public transport 'hotspot' information and travel advice published by TfL today is available at <a href="http://www.tfl.gov.uk/2012">tfl.gov.uk/2012</a> </li>
<li>An updated set of this information, including weekend and Paralympic data for stations, will be released by TfL in January, following confirmation of the detailed impact of road events.&nbsp; In total, TfL expects to release detailed information on around 70 Tube and DLR stations and is making clear which of those yet to be released have demand patterns similar to those already published </li>
<li>In March, TfL will release data suitable for journey planning systems detailing the Games-time restrictions on London's road network </li>
<li>Quotes from a range of business leaders and organisations on how they are planning to stay ahead of the Games are attached and available from the TfL Press Office </li>
<li>TfL and London 2012 provide free travel advice to business programmes to companies operating in areas of London and the rest of the UK that will be affected by the Games. Four hundred major companies, employing more than half a million people, have already benefited from tailored, site specific advice, a further 497 businesses employing 200 people or less have already attended area based workshops, while around 100 companies employing more than 200 people at multiple locations have attended or will be attending themed workshops to assist them </li>
<li>&pound;6.5 billion has been invested in upgrading and extending transport links to increase capacity and improve services in the capital. This is already providing an early legacy of better transport options, particularly for people living in east London, which will benefit millions of people and support economic development for generations to come </li>
<li>The Olympic Route Network (ORN) will come into operation a couple of days before the Olympic Games and will be removed as soon as possible once the Olympics are over. It will not be in operation again until a couple of days ahead of the Paralympic Games, and will be removed as soon as possible after the Paralympics have finished. General traffic can, with the exception of Birdcage Walk, Constitution Hill and The Mall, use the entire 109 mile ORN (which makes up just 1 per cent of the London's road network). Only one third of the ORN will have Games Lanes, which are only implemented where more than one lane is available, and which are open to the Games family - the media (who make up the largest element of the Games family), athletes, officials, Games workers, sponsors and IOC members. To keep traffic moving along the routes some temporary traffic changes will be necessary. These changes might include different signal timings, side road closures or the suspension of parking, loading and waiting bays. The ORN is necessary in order to get all athletes, officials and the media to their Games events on time, and has been a feature of all Host Cities contracts with the IOC since the Atlanta Games in 1996</li></ul>

     

        
        
        
